# Development Guidelines

## Pre-release / Backward compatibility

The project is not released. **Backward compatibility is not a requirement.** Do not preserve backward compatibility with previous APIs, state shapes, or file formats. Prefer straightforward changes and clean design over compatibility layers or migration paths.

## Code Quality Standards

- Write clean, canonical, and DRY code
- Avoid smart hacks, obscure patterns, or clever tricks
- Add comments ONLY when they add significant value
- Use strict TypeScript with all compiler warnings enabled
- Follow ESLint rules for code quality

## JSDoc Documentation

Add JSDoc comments to:

- All public methods and functions
- All exported interfaces, types, and classes
- Complex private methods where the logic is non-obvious

JSDoc should include:

- Brief description of what the method/class does
- @param tags for all parameters
- @returns tag for return values
- @throws tag if the method can throw errors

## Voice-Only UX Requirements

- **Voice is central**—production flows always require Vosk; `skipWakeWord` is for debug/tests only
- Screen stays on but no visual interaction required
- All feedback must be audible
- Users cannot see errors, so voice feedback is critical
- Every error condition needs a voice response

### Gameplay voice-turn invariant

For each **successful** gameplay user utterance (after orchestrator handling and any app follow-up such as turn advance or revenge announcement), the player must hear **at least one** `speak()` before returning to listening.

**Exceptions:** validation / LLM failure paths that already speak an error; name collection (setup) handled by `NameCollector` without this policy; any future `handleTranscript` flag for intentional listen-only flows.

**Implementation:** [`MeteredSpeechService`](src/voice/metered-speech-service.ts) counts `speak` calls per turn; [`applySilentSuccessFallback`](src/voice/gameplay-voice-policy.ts) runs in [`KaliAppCore`](src/kali-app-core.ts) when the turn was successful but still silent. Hints from the orchestrator (`VoiceOutcomeHints`, e.g. fork resolved without `NARRATE`) select deterministic i18n lines. Sound effects alone do not satisfy the invariant.

## Testing Requirements

When to run checks and fix: see the **Full-check after agentic changes** rule.

### Test File Standards

Test files (`*.test.ts`) have more flexibility:

- **ESLint**: Pragmatic approach - use `/* eslint-disable */` for intentional test patterns
- **TypeScript**: Use `any`, `as unknown`, or `@ts-nocheck` for complex mocks when needed
- **Focus**: Tests should be readable and maintainable, not die on strict typing hills
- **Adversarial tests**: Files testing malformed/adversarial data may use `@ts-nocheck`
- **Production code**: Must maintain full type safety and lint compliance

## Key Patterns

### Primitive Actions

The orchestrator only understands these primitives:

- `NARRATE` - Speak to players via TTS
- `RESET_GAME` - Reset game to initial state
- `SET_STATE` - Set value in game state (user corrections/overrides)
- `PLAYER_ROLLED` - Report dice roll; orchestrator calculates position
- `PLAYER_ANSWERED` - Report player answer (path choice, fight/flee, etc.)

### State Machine

Audio pipeline follows: idle → listening → processing → speaking

### LLM Swappability

- All LLM clients implement `ILLMClient` interface
- Switching providers is a one-line change

### Processing Lock

- Prevents overlapping LLM requests
- Ensures serial processing of voice commands
